{ Annotated by IM Nitish Belurkar https://lichess.org/@/kingnb }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 { Rapport, known for his wide and erratic range in his repertoire, chose the Kan variation } 5. a3 Nf6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Be3 Be7 8. Bc4 { An opening error, allows black tempo when he wants to get b5 } 8... O-O 9. Qe2 b5 10. Ba2 Qc7 11. g4?! { Supi tries to surprise Rapport, but the king is still in the center } (11. O-O-O Nc6 12. Nxc6 Qxc6 13. Bd4 Rb8 { Would have been the way to continue with complex equality for both sides }) 11... d5! { Rapport hits the center, where the king is, but has a hidden motive in this move } 12. exd5 Bxa3!! { The hidden motive behind d5! } 13. Nd1 (13. bxa3?? Qxc3+ 14. Kf1 Qxa1+ $19) 13... e5 14. Nf5 Bxf5 15. gxf5 Bb4+ 16. c3 Bd6 $17 { Black has the better setup, active pieces, better pawn structure, and a safer King! } 17. Bg5 Nbd7 18. Ne3 b4 19. Qc4 Qb8 20. Qh4 Kh8 21. Nc4 a5 22. O-O!? { White King looks for safety in a fort without doors, as the g2 pawn stays missing } 22... Bc5 23. Rad1 a4?! { Black lets the advantage slip } (23... b3 24. Bb1 a4 $15 { As the white squared bishop sits at home blocked by his own ugly pawns }) 24. cxb4 Qxb4 25. Bd2 Qb8 26. Bc3 Bb4?! 27. d6? (27. Bxe5! Nxe5 28. Nxe5 Qxe5 29. Qxb4 { Would have helped white restore balance in the game and hold on! }) 27... Bxc3 28. bxc3 a3 { Passed pawn must be pushed! } 29. Rfe1 Ra4 30. Qg3 Re8 31. Rb1 (31. Rxe5! Nxe5 (31... Rc8! { The right way to play for black } 32. Rd4 Rcxc4 33. Rxc4 Rxc4 34. Bxc4 Qb1+ 35. Kg2 a2 36. Bxa2 Qxa2 $15) 32. Nxe5 { Activates the bishop and the knight, forcing black to return the exchange } 32... Rxe5 33. Qxe5 $14) (31. Nxe5?? { Is not a free pawn } 31... Nxe5 32. Rxe5 Rg4 $19) 31... Qa8 32. Rb4 e4 33. Qe3 Rxb4 34. cxb4 Qd5 35. Qf4 h6 36. f3 e3! { The pawn is poisoned } 37. Rxe3 (37. Nxe3 Qxa2 $19) 37... Qd1+ 38. Kg2 Qc2+ 39. Kh3 Rxe3 40. Qxe3 Qxa2 41. Nxa3 Qd5 { Rapport with a beautiful display of his dynamic abilities, as he wins his fist game in the event! } 0-1


