{ Annotated by IM Nitish Belurkar https://lichess.org/@/kingnb }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O { Diptayan rarely ever played the Marshall, and chose to surprise the 2 time World Championship challenger, Ian Nepomniachtchi } 8. a4 b4 9. d4 { Nepo decided to go for the anti Marsall setup, denying black the opportunity to play d5 } 9... d6 (9... Nxd4? 10. Bxf7+!! Kxf7 (10... Rxf7 11. Nxe5 Nc6 12. Nxf7 Kxf7 13. e5 $18 { White dominates the black pieces }) 11. Nxe5+ Kg8 12. Qxd4 $16) (9... exd4 10. e5 Ne8 11. Bd5 $16 { Ties down black }) 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Nbd2 a5 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Qe2 Bc5 14. Nf3 (14. Nc4 { The more natural plan for white } 14... Ng4 15. Ne3 Qh4 16. h3 Nf6 17. Nf5) 14... Qe7 15. h3? { Nepo gets too casual } (15. Be3 Ba6 16. Bc4 Bxe3 17. Bxa6 Bb6 18. Bc4 { Would have been a balanced game }) 15... Ba6! { Comes with brute force and a tactical resource for black } 16. Qd1? (16. Bc4 { The very natural move } 16... Bxf2+ 17. Kxf2 (17. Qxf2 { Would have been the most ideal way to play for white } 17... Bxc4 18. Bg5 h6 19. Bxf6 Qxf6 20. Qc5 Qb6 21. Qxb6 cxb6 22. Nxe5 Be6 $15) 17... Qc5+ 18. Be3 Qxc4 19. Qxc4 Bxc4 20. Nxe5 Nxe4+ $17 { Black is just a pawn up }) 16... Rad8 17. Nd2 Bd4 { Black is very comfortable, white's pieces are tied down } 18. Qf3 Bxb2! { A tactical shot, collecting a pawn } 19. Bxb2 Rxd2 20. Qe3 Rdd8 21. f4 { Whites only desperate attempt to create counterplay } 21... exf4 22. Qxf4 c5! { Diptayan spots the crucial moment and the essential move, to keep his position favourable and latch on to the advantage } 23. Bd5 (23. Bxf6 Qxf6 24. Qxf6 gxf6 $19 { With an extra pawn that will roll down the Queen side }) 23... Nxd5 24. exd5 Qd6! { It is time to force the Queens off the board } 25. Qg4 (25. Qxd6 Rxd6 26. Rad1 Bc4 $19) 25... Qg6 26. Qxg6 hxg6 27. Rad1 Rd7 28. d6 Rfd8 29. Be5 Bb7 { Changing the course towards the next weakness, the pawn on a4 } 30. Bg3 Bc6 31. Ra1 f6 32. Kf2 Kf7 33. h4 c4 34. Red1 Re8 35. Bf4 c3 36. g3 Re6 37. Rd4 g5 38. hxg5 fxg5 39. Bxg5 Rdxd6 40. Rc4 Rd5 41. Be3 Rde5 42. Rf1 Kg8 43. g4 Rxe3 44. Rxc6 Re2+ 45. Kf3 Rxc6 46. Kxe2 Rd6 { A very clean tecnhique and display from Diptayan that helped him get his biggest career victory and head on to Round 3 after eliminating the Russian powerhouse } 0-1


