{ Annotated by IM Nitish Belurkar https://lichess.org/@/kingnb }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 d5 { Abasov choses to play the more direct and forcing line } 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. O-O Be7 7. Re1 f6 8. Bd2 { Andrey Esipenko chooses a not so popular line, to put Abasov off guard and prep } (8. d4 { The most common choice in practice } 8... Nb6 9. Bb5 { And it goes on }) 8... Bg4 9. h3 Bh5 10. Nc3 Nxc3?! (10... Nb6 11. Bb3 Nd4 12. g4 Nxb3 13. axb3 Bg6 { An equal but complex position }) 11. Bxc3 Qd6? (11... Bf7 12. Bxf7+ Kxf7 13. Qe2 Re8 $14 { White enjoys more flexibility and comfort in the position }) 12. Rb1 (12. b4! { Starts the roll of the pawns! } 12... O-O-O 13. Rb1 f5 14. b5 Nd4 15. Bxd4 exd4 16. Re6 Qc5 17. Qe1 $18) 12... O-O-O? (12... a6 13. a4 Bf7 14. Bxf7+ Kxf7 $14) 13. b4 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 $18 Nd4 15. Bxd4 Qxd4 16. c3 Qd7 (16... Qxc3 17. Ba6! { Seals it! } 17... bxa6 18. Rec1 Qd4 19. Qa8+ Kd7 20. Qc6+ Kc8 21. Qxc7#) 17. d4 Bd6 18. Ba6!! { Andrey Esipenkoo spots it! } 18... c6 (18... bxa6 19. Qa8#) 19. b5 c5 20. b6 bxa6 21. bxa7 Qxa7 22. Qc6+ Bc7 23. Qe6+ Rd7 24. dxc5 Qxc5 25. Qxa6+ Kd8 26. Qa8+ { The forcing line chosen by Abasov did not work out well, Andrey Esipenko took the advantage and made sure to convert it to a full point! } 1-0


