{ Annotated by IM Nitish Belurkar https://lichess.org/@/kingnb }
1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2 Bf5 4. O-O e6 5. d3 h6 6. c4 dxc4 7. dxc4 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Nf6 9. Bf4 Nbd7 10. Nc3 g5 11. Be3 Ng4 12. Bd2 Bc2 { Deviating from the general course of games } (12... Bc5 13. Be1 Nge5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Ne4 { and the game goes on }) 13. Rdc1 Bg6 14. h4?! { A very ambitious move from Aravindh } 14... Nge5 (14... gxh4! 15. Nxh4 Bh7 16. Be4 f5 17. Bc2 O-O-O $15 { Black enjoys a superior position, with more active pieces }) 15. Nxe5 Nxe5 16. Ne4 Bxe4 17. Bxe4 f5 18. Bc2 Rg8 19. hxg5 hxg5 20. c5 Rd8 (20... Bxc5!? 21. Bb3 (21. Bxf5? Bxf2+ 22. Kxf2 exf5 23. Rc5 Ng4+ $15 { An extra pawn for black }) 21... Bd4 22. Bxe6 Rf8 23. Rd1 { White is prefered due to the 2 active bishops }) 21. Ba5 Rd7 22. Bb3 Rg6 23. Kg2 Bg7 24. Rh1 Ke7 25. f3 Nf7 26. Rab1 Bd4 27. Bb4 Be3 28. Rh7 { Both players are actively improving their own camp! } 28... Rh6 29. Rxh6 Nxh6 30. Rh1 Nf7 31. Bc2 Rd5 32. g4? { Panic sets in, as Aravindh is makes the first grave error } 32... Bd2! { Karthik spots it! } (32... Bxc5 33. e4 fxe4 34. fxe4 Bxb4 35. exd5 cxd5 { Would be interesting but not ideal as black }) 33. Ba3 (33. Bxd2? Rxd2 $19 { The activity of the rook decides the fate }) (33. e4 fxe4 34. fxe4 Rd4 35. Ba3 Bb4 36. Bxb4 Rxb4 37. b3 Rb5 $19 { The pawn on c5 is lost }) 33... fxg4 34. fxg4 Rd4 35. Kg3 Bf4+ (35... Ne5! { More decisive } 36. Rh7+ Kf8 37. Rxb7 Rxg4+ 38. Kf2 Rf4+ 39. Kg2 Be3 $19 { White king faces the wrath of the pieces surroundig them, as white pieces are wandering on the other end }) 36. Kf2 Be5 37. Bg6 Rxg4 $17 { An extra pawn } 38. Rh7 Rf4+ 39. Kg2 Kf8 40. b3 Rg4+ 41. Kf3 Rf4+ 42. Kg2 Rf6 43. Bd3 Bd4 44. b4 { Looking to get the dark squared bishop back into action } 44... a6 (44... Rf2+! 45. Kg3 Rf1 { Not allowing any counterplay for black } 46. Kg2 Rg1+ 47. Kh2 g4 $19) 45. Rh1 Ne5 46. Rh8+ Ke7 47. Rh7+ Rf7?! (47... Kf8 48. Rh8+ Kf7 49. Rh7+ Kg8 { Black must avoid the exchange of the rook } 50. Rxb7 Rf2+ $19) 48. Bc1 Nxd3? { White now gets his chance to bouce back } (48... Bc3 49. Bxg5+ Ke8 50. Rh8+ Kd7 $17 { Black still in the driver seat }) 49. Bxg5+ Ke8 (49... Bf6!? 50. Bxf6+ { Essential to play this first } (50. Rxf7+?? Kxf7 51. Bxf6 Kxf6 52. exd3 Ke5 53. Kf3 Kd4 54. Ke2 Kc3 $19 { The black King is faster and sweeps the white pawns on the Queen side }) 50... Kxf6 51. Rxf7+ Kxf7 52. exd3 Kf6 53. d4 e5 54. Kf3! exd4 55. Ke4) 50. Rxf7 Ne1+ 51. Kf1 Kxf7 52. Kxe1 Kg6 53. Bd2 Kf5 { White has a more active king, a better bishop, and safe pawns, but there are not enough weaknesses for white } 54. Kd1 Ke4 55. Kc2 Be3 56. Bc3?! (56. Be1 Bh6 57. Bf2 { Essential to hold on to the e3 square }) 56... Bf4 57. a3 Bg5 (57... Ke3? 58. Bd2+ Ke4 59. Bxf4 Kxf4 60. Kd3) 58. Bb2 Bh4 59. Bc3? Bf2 (59... Ke3! { The black king gets in } 60. Kd1 Be7 61. Bb2 a5 62. Bc3 axb4 63. axb4 Bh4 64. Ba1 Ke4 65. Kd2 (65. Kc2 Be1 66. Kb3 Ke3 $19) 65... Bf2 { Intending to force exchanges } 66. Bf6 e5 $19) 60. Bd2 Kd4 61. Kb3 Bg3 62. Bg5 e5 63. Kc2? (63. Bd8 Ke3 64. Ka4! e4 65. Ka5 { White heads towards the black pawns } 65... Kxe2 66. Kb6 Kd3 67. Bg5 Kc4 68. Kxb7 Kb5 69. Be3) 63... Kc4! $17 { The black king is positioned perfectly to take a step to either side } 64. Bd8 e4 65. Kb2 Bf4 66. Kc2 Bh6 67. Bc7 Bg5 { The white bishop is restricted to the diagonal to prevent black from pushing a5 } 68. Kb2 Kd4 { The direction of the king is decided } 69. Kc2 Ke3 70. Kd1 Bf6 71. Bh2 Bb2 72. Bg1+ Kf4 73. Kd2 Bxa3 74. Bh2+ Kf5 75. Kc3 Bc1 76. Bd6 Bg5 77. Kc4 Bf6 78. Bg3 Kg4 79. Bf2 Kf4 { The king forces its way in } 80. Bd4 Bh4 81. Kc3 Be1+ 82. Kc4 Bd2 83. Bf2 Be3 { The long way in } 84. Bh4 Kg4 85. Be1 Kh3 86. Kb3 Kg2 87. Kc2 Kf1 88. Kd1 Bd4 89. Bd2 Bf6 { A beautiful display by Karthik, manouvering the king and bishop masterfully to get the better of Aravindh, and head on to Round 3! } (89... e3) 0-1


