{ Annotated by IM Nitish Belurkar https://lichess.org/@/kingnb }
1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 Be7 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 c6 7. h3 { An interesting idea by Titas, making space for the bishop on h2, and also hinting at a possible g4! } 7... Qb6 8. Qc2 g6 9. e3 Bf5 10. Qc1 O-O 11. g4!? { Here it is! White waited for black to 0-0 } 11... Be4 12. Be2 Nbd7 13. O-O Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Qd8 15. Qc2 { The play for white is easier } 15... Ne8 16. e4 dxe4 17. Bxe4 Ndf6 18. Rad1 Nc7?! (18... Nxe4 { Getting rid of the bishop pair, would have been more ideal for So to do so } 19. Qxe4 Bg5 20. Bg3 Nf6 21. Qf3 Nd5 { The position completely neutralised }) 19. Bg2 Qd7 20. Qb3 (20. d5! { Would have given white dominant chances } 20... Nfxd5?? (20... cxd5 21. Qb3 { The black defenders can easily be targeted } 21... Rad8 22. Bxc7 Qxc7 23. g5 Nh5 24. Nxd5 $18 { With an extremely comfortable and active position for white }) (20... Ncxd5 21. g5 Nh5 22. Bxd5 Qc8! { A very tough find, albeit, a necessary one for black to stay alive } (22... Nxf4?? 23. Bxf7+! Rxf7 24. Rxd7 $18) (22... cxd5 23. Nxd5 Nxf4?? 24. Nf6+ Bxf6 25. Rxd7 $18) 23. Qe4 Nxf4 24. Qxf4 cxd5 25. Nxd5 $14) 21. Bxc7 Qxc7 22. Nxd5 $18) 20... Ncd5 21. Be5 Rfe8?! 22. g5! { White now finally decides, to commit to the push! } 22... Nxc3 (22... Nh5 23. Nxd5 cxd5 24. Qxd5 Qf5 25. h4 $18 { With an healthy extra pawn for white }) 23. gxf6 Nxd1 24. fxe7 Nxf2 25. Bf6 Rxe7 26. Bxe7 Qxe7 27. Rxf2 $18 { A position many would giveup as black, but not Wesley said, not So early! } 27... Rd8 28. d5 cxd5 29. Bxd5 Qg5+ 30. Bg2 Rd7 31. Qc3 Qe7 32. Rf1 b6 33. Re1 Qd8 34. Qe5 Rd1 35. Rxd1 Qxd1+ 36. Kh2 { White has a piece, for just 2 pawns, but the king is weak, and the black Queen eyes any potential perpetuals } 36... h5 37. a3 (37. Qb8+ Kg7 38. Qxa7?? { Is not the way white would want to grab the pawn } 38... Qd6+ 39. Kg1 Qd4+ 40. Kf1 Qd1+ 41. Kf2 Qd2+ { With perpetual checks to follow }) 37... h4 38. Qe8+ Kg7 39. Qe3 Kg8 40. Qf2 Qd8 41. Kg1 Qg5 42. Qd4 Qg3 43. Kf1 { White treads carefully, to get the king to safety, and avoid any incoming repetitions } 43... Kh7 44. Qc3 Qg5 45. Bc6 Qe7 46. Bf3 Qd6 47. Be2 Qf4+ 48. Ke1 f5 49. Kd1 { The King eading towards the Queen side, where the barricade of small pawns will help white shield his king } 49... Kh6 50. Qd2 Kg5 51. Bb5? { Allows the trade of Queens in a position where the black king is into the white camp } (51. Qxf4+?? { Fails } 51... Kxf4 52. Bd3 Kg3 53. Ke2 Kxh3 54. Kf3 Kh2 { And the 3 black pawns neutralise the effect of the extra white bishop }) (51. Qd8+ Kh6 52. Qd3 $18 { Preserving the queen would have been the right thing to do }) 51... Qxd2+ 52. Kxd2 Kf4 53. Be8 g5 54. Bd7 g4 55. hxg4 fxg4 56. Ke2 g3 57. Bc6 { Titas, playing whtie, wants to push hard, as he does not want to believe this has slipped away } 57... Ke5 58. Ke3 h3?? { Black breaks open his own fort } (58... Kd6 59. Bg2 Ke5 60. a4 a5 61. b3 Kd6 62. Kd4 Ke6 63. Bh3+ Kd6 { Black holds on with the pawn on h4 and g3, as black cannot reach them in time and defend his Queen side too }) 59. Bd7! h2 60. Bc6 $18 { The bishop now overpowers the 2 pawns } 60... Kd6 61. Bg2 Kc5 62. b3 a5 63. Kd3 b5 64. Bf3 Kd6 65. Kd4 Ke6 66. Be4 Kf6 67. Kd5 Kg5 68. Ke5 Kg4 69. Bg2 Kg5 70. a4?? (70. Ke4 Kg4 71. Ke3 Kf5 72. Kf3 a4 73. b4 Ke5 74. Ke3 Kf5 75. Bc6 Kg4 76. Ke2 Kf4 77. Kf1 $18 { The right technique! }) 70... b4 71. Ke4 Kg4 72. Ke3 { Wesley SO resigned in a completely drawn positions } 1-0


