{ Annotated by IM Nitish Belurkar https://lichess.org/@/kingnb }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Bxc6 { Opting for a not so common line, the delayed exchange variation in the Spanish } 6... dxc6 7. Re1 Nd7 8. c3 c5 9. d4 exd4 10. cxd4 O-O 11. Nc3 b5 { Hans being ambitious } (11... cxd4 { A simpler way to play this position } 12. Nxd4 Ne5 13. Bf4 Bf6 14. Nd5 c6 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 16. Bg3) 12. a4 b4?! { This makes weaknesses for the black side } 13. Nd5 Bb7 14. Nxe7+ Qxe7 15. d5 Rfe8?! (15... f5! { Black hits the center, and this would give great chances for black } 16. e5 f4 { Hampering the bishops movement } 17. Qb3 c4! 18. Qxc4 Qc5 19. Qd4 (19. Qxc5 Nxc5 20. Bd2 a5 21. e6 Nd3 22. e7 Rfe8 23. Re4 Nxb2 $15) 19... Bxd5 20. Bd2 Qxd4 21. Nxd4 c5) 16. Bg5 Qd6 17. Qd2 $16 { White now has a dominant position } 17... a5 18. Bf4 Qb6 19. Rac1 { The pawns in the center overpower the Black bishop } 19... Rad8 20. Qc2 Ba6 21. Nd2 Rc8 22. b3 Qf6 23. Bg3 c6 24. d6! { The pawn finally takes a step ahead, when now Black has blocked the a8-h1 diagonal himself } 24... Rcd8 25. Nf3 Qg6 26. Nh4 Qe6 27. Nf5 { The knight reroutes itself into the Black territory } 27... c4 28. Nd4 Qf6 29. e5 Qg6 (29... Nxe5 30. Bxe5 Rxe5 31. Rxe5 Qxe5 32. Nxc6 { Forked! } 32... cxb3 33. Qxb3 Qg5 34. Rd1 Rd7 35. Qe3 Qxe3 36. fxe3 g6 37. Nxa5 $18 { White has 2 many passed pawns }) 30. Qxg6 hxg6 31. bxc4 c5 32. Nc6 Ra8 (32... Rc8 33. Ne7+ $18) 33. Nxa5 Bc8 34. Nb3 Rxa4 35. f4 { The pawns at the center of the board pin down the Black pieces } 35... Ra3 36. Rb1 Ba6 37. Bf2 Rc8 (37... Bxc4 38. Nxc5 Nxc5 39. Bxc5 $18 { Black is helpless as the b4 pawn falls too }) 38. Nxc5! { There was no saving the pawn } 38... Nxc5 39. Bxc5 Bxc4 (39... Rxc5 40. d7 { Unstoppable } 40... Rd3 41. Rbd1 Rxd7 42. Rxd7 $18) 40. Bxb4 Rd3 41. Rbd1 Rxd1 42. Rxd1 $18 { White is up 2 healthy pawns } 42... Be6 43. Ba5 (43. d7?? Rd8) 43... Bd7 44. Rb1 Kf8 45. Bc7 Ke8 46. Ra1 { White is a bit slow in his plans, the Black bishop making it tough for the white pawns to advance any further } 46... Be6 47. Kf2 Kd7 48. h3 Bd5 49. g4 Ra8 50. Ba5 (50. Rxa8 { Would have made life easier for White } 50... Bxa8 51. Ke3 Bg2 52. h4 Bh3 53. Kf3 Bf1 54. f5 { Too many pawns for Black to play against }) 50... Ke6 51. f5+ gxf5 52. gxf5+ Kd7 (52... Kxf5 53. d7 $18 { The pawn finally promotes }) (52... Kxe5 53. d7 $18 { Faces similar fate }) 53. Ke3 Rh8 54. Kd4 Bb7 55. Be1 f6 56. Bg3 (56. e6+! Kxd6 57. Rc1 { A move that finishes the game on the spot! } 57... Rd8 (57... Ke7 58. Rc7+ $18) (57... Bc6 58. Bg3+ Ke7 59. Rxc6 $18) 58. Bb4#) 56... fxe5+ 57. Kxe5 Re8+ 58. Kf4 Kxd6 59. Kg5+ Kc6 (59... Kd7 { Would have been better resistance } 60. Rd1+ Kc8 61. Rc1+ Kd8 62. Bc7+ Ke7 63. Be5 Rc8 64. Rd1 $16) (59... Ke7? 60. Ra7 $18) 60. Rc1+ Kb6 61. h4 Bc8 62. Bc7+ Kb7 63. Bd6 Kb6 64. Bc5+ Kb7 65. Bd4?! { White misses the trick } 65... Re4!? { A great practical choice from Hans } 66. Rxc8? (66. Bxg7? Bxf5 67. Kxf5 Rxh4 { Is known to be a draw }) (66. Bf2 Bd7 67. Rc5 $16 { Is good practical chances for white }) 66... Kxc8 { White has let the advantage slip away } 67. Bxg7 Kd7 68. h5 Ke7 { The Black king rushes to stop the pawns, aided by the rook } 69. h6 Kf7 70. Bf6 Kg8 71. Kg6 Rg4+ 72. Bg5 Rg1?? { g1, The only square along the g file the rook should not have touched } (72... Rg2 73. f6 Rf2 74. h7+ Kh8 75. f7 Rxf7 76. Kxf7 Kxh7) (72... Rg3 { Works as well for Black }) 73. f6 Rf1 74. Be3! { This is the reason why Rg1 fails, white now holds the g1 square } 74... Rf3 75. h7+ Kh8 76. f7 Rg3+ (76... Rxf7 77. Bd4+ (77. Kxf7?? Kxh7) 77... Rf6+ 78. Bxf6#) 77. Bg5 { 2 Lodici takes the lead and then goes on to eliminate Hans Niemann in the Round } 1-0


