{ Annotated by IM Nitish Belurkar https://lichess.org/@/kingnb }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 d6 4. c3 f5?! { A very offbeat line by Nihal, opting to surprise his opponent early on in the tie-breaks } 5. d3 f4 { Black on a mission, to initiate the attack on the kingside and stop white pieces from heading there } 6. h4 Qf6 7. b4 { White heads to the queenside } 7... Nh6 8. Nbd2 Ng4 9. Bb2 Bd7 10. a4 Be7 11. Qe2 Nd8 12. d4! { It is now time to break open, White takes action } 12... Nf7 13. Bb3 O-O-O? { A very ambitious decision, to walk into the fire } (13... O-O 14. O-O-O Kh8 $14 { White stays better, but both kings are safer for the moment }) 14. b5! { Rolling the pawns towards the enemy king } 14... Kb8 15. a5 Bc8 16. b6 c6 17. a6! { The 2 pawns invincible, taking charge of opening the gates to the black king } 17... Rd7 (17... axb6? 18. a7+ Ka8 19. Nc4 b5 20. Nb6#) (17... bxa6 18. d5 c5 19. bxa7+ Kxa7 20. Bc4 $18) 18. d5 axb6 19. axb7 Bxb7 20. dxc6 (20. Ng5! { A move that would speed up the devastation } 20... Nxg5 (20... h5 21. dxc6 Bxc6 22. Bxf7 $18 { Wins a piece, and soon the game }) 21. Qxg4 $18 { And black will lose a piece }) 20... Bxc6 21. Qa6 Rc8 22. Bd5 Bxd5 23. exd5 Kc7 { Black tries to flee the king to the side where his pieces rest } 24. Nc4! Rb8 25. Qa7+ Rb7 26. Qa8 (26. Qa4! { Threatens instant checkmate } 26... Nd8 (26... Kd8 27. Qa8+ Kc7 28. Ra7 Rxa7 29. Qxa7+ Kc8 30. Nxb6+ Kd8 31. Qb8# { Would be game over }) 27. Na3 Kc8 28. Nb5 $18) 26... Rd8 27. Qa4 b5 28. Qa5+ Kd7 { The rook move to d8 has made space for the Black king } 29. Qa6 Ke8 30. Qxb7 bxc4 31. Qc6+? { White has let the massive advantage slip away } (31. Ra7 e4 32. Ng5 Nfe5 33. Nxe4 Nd3+ 34. Kd2 Qe5 35. Ng5 $18 { White is better, but the position remains very complicated }) 31... Kf8 32. Qxc4 Qg6 33. h5 Qf5 34. Nd2 Qc2 (34... Ng5! { Would turn the tide, and is now blacks turn to push } 35. Ra4 h6 36. Ba3 e4 37. Nxe4 f3 38. gxf3 Qxf3 $15 { Black with the safer king and the better pieces, now targets the fragile white king }) 35. Bc1 (35. Qb3 Qf5 36. c4 $14 { Would be the more ideal way to play for white }) 35... Nf6 36. f3 e4? { Black rushes again?! } (36... Qf5 37. Ne4 Nxh5 38. Ra7 Qg6 39. Qc7 Re8 40. O-O Ng5 $13 { Unclear, but a balanced position }) 37. Qb3 Qd3 38. c4 Qxb3 39. Nxb3 { White is now comfortably up material, as the queens are forced off the board } 39... Ne5 40. fxe4 Nxe4 41. O-O { After 40 moves, White finally finds a spot to rest his king away from the storm } 41... f3 42. gxf3 Ng3 43. Rf2 Nxh5 44. Nd4 Rc8 45. c5!? dxc5 (45... Rxc5 46. Ne6+ $18) 46. Ne6+ Kf7 47. Ra7 { Tying down the king and the bishop } 47... Nf6 48. Ng5+ { White can sense the final blow incoming } 48... Kf8 49. Re2 Ng6 50. d6 Bxd6 51. Ne6+ Kg8 52. Rxg7+ Kh8 53. Bb2 { All the White pieces are now in action, the king that ran away from the storm, finds himself back in another one } 53... Nf4 54. Bxf6 Nxe2+ 55. Kf2 h5 56. Rc7+ (56. Ng5 { Would lead to a quicker mate } 56... Bg3+ 57. Kxe2 Re8+ 58. Re7+ Kg8 59. Rxe8#) 56... Kg8 57. Rxc8+ Kf7 58. Kxe2 { 1-0 White wins. } 1-0


