{ Annotated by IM Nitish Belurkar https://lichess.org/@/kingnb }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 { Black opts for classical variation } 7. Qd2 a6 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. O-O-O { A line that has been trending in the recent times } 9... Be7 (9... d5 { The immediate push in the center makes play tough for Black } 10. Qe3 Be7 11. Bxf6 gxf6 (11... Bxf6? 12. exd5 cxd5 13. Nxd5 $18) 12. Bc4 Bb7 13. Bb3 $14) 10. Bxf6 { Forces black to take with the g pawn } 10... gxf6 (10... Bxf6? 11. Qxd6 $16) 11. Bc4 Bb7 12. Rhe1 Qa5 13. Kb1 { White has his camp ready, and king tucked into safety } 13... Qc5? { The queen does not belong there } (13... h5!? { A very generic plan of the classical, avoiding Qh6 for white, and intending to push further } 14. h4 Rd8 15. Bb3 d5) 14. Bb3 d5 15. Na4 $16 { strikes at the misplaced queen } 15... Qa7 (15... Qb4 16. c3 Qa5 17. Qe3 $16 { A flurry of threats }) 16. c4 { Harikrishna decides to strike at the center where the Black king rests } 16... Rd8? 17. cxd5 cxd5 18. Nc3! { The white knight retreats as it's job is done, and opens space for the bishop on a4 } 18... dxe4 (18... h5 19. exd5 Kf8 20. Qe2 e5 21. f4 $18 { Only helps black prolong the inevitable }) 19. Ba4+ Kf8 20. Qh6+ { Hunting the Black king } 20... Kg8 21. Rxd8+ Bxd8 22. Re3 { All the pieces in action } 22... Bc7 23. Nxe4 Bxe4+ 24. Rxe4 f5 25. Rxe6 { A fancy finish to an exceptional game from Harikrishna } 1-0


