{ Annotated by IM Nitish Belurkar https://lichess.org/@/kingnb }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 { The World Champion opted to play the Italian } 4... Bc5 5. O-O d6 6. c3 a5 { Frederik playing a very mainstream idea, and both locked in and ready for a long game } 7. Re1 O-O 8. h3 h6 9. Nbd2 Bb6 10. a4 Bd7 { A rare move chosen by Frederik } (10... Ne7 11. Nf1 Ng6 12. Ng3 c6 13. Bb3 d5 { A common idea used by Black in the setups against the Italian }) 11. b3 Be6!? { Defying the usual opening principles, of not moving the same piece twice } 12. Bb2 { Gukesh thus defends the c3 pawn, anticipating d5 } (12. Nf1 { played in games before } 12... d5 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Bd2 (14. Nxe5? { Does not work } 14... Nxc3 15. Qc2 Nxe5 16. Rxe5 Bxc4 17. bxc4 Bd4 18. Re1 Ne2+ 19. Qxe2 Bxa1 $19) 14... Qf6 { fizzles out into relatively dry equality }) 12... Kh8 (12... d5? 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Rxe5 $16 { The c3 pawn is now defended }) 13. Ra2 Nh5 14. Nf1 (14. Nxe5?? { Black generally has to keep an eye out for a discover attack like this } 14... Qh4 { Helps Black get the decisive advantage } (14... dxe5? 15. Qxh5 $14) 15. d4 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Qxf2+ 17. Kh2 Qf4+ 18. Kh1 Ng3+ 19. Kh2 Nf1+ 20. Kh1 Qh2#) 14... Nf4 15. Bc1 Qf6 16. Ng3 g5!? { Frederik realises it is now time to pose threats for the White king } 17. Nh2 Qg6 { Keeping all the pawn breaks on radar } 18. Be3 d5 { The time is right to breakthrough } 19. exd5 Bxd5 20. Bxb6 cxb6 21. Nf3 Rad8 { The position remains equal, but very dynamic } 22. Rd2 Bxc4 23. dxc4 f6 24. Ne4 Rxd2 25. Qxd2 Rd8 26. Qe3 f5 27. Ng3 Nd3 28. Rd1 (28. Re2 { An essential move, to keep the balance in the position } 28... f4 29. Qe4 Kh7 30. Qxg6+ Kxg6 31. Ne4 Nc1 32. Rb2 Rd1+ 33. Kh2 Nd3 34. Rd2 { As the dust settles, both sides head into an equal endgame }) 28... f4 29. Qe4 Kh7 30. Qxg6+ Kxg6 31. Ne4 Kf5 $15 { White now has to be more precise, Black, has more freedom } 32. Nfd2 (32. g4+!? { An alternative } 32... fxg3 33. Nxg3+ Ke6 34. Kf1 Nc5 35. Rxd8 Nxd8 36. Nd2 $15) 32... Nc5 (32... h5! { Black should expand towards the White king } 33. f3 Nc5 34. Re1 g4 $15) 33. Re1 (33. g4+! { An essential move } 33... Ke6 34. Rb1 Rd3 35. Kf1 Ke7 36. Nxc5 bxc5 37. Ne4 Nd8 38. Ke2 Rxh3 39. Rd1 Nf7 40. Nxc5 { White holds on }) 33... Nd3 (33... h5 $15 { Important for black to keep expanding }) 34. Rb1 { Gukesh realises he has the chance to equalise } (34. Rd1 h5 $15 { Black would not want to repeat again }) 34... h5 35. Kf1 Nc5 36. f3 Rd3 37. Kf2 g4 { Time to make the break! } 38. hxg4+ hxg4 39. Re1? (39. Rh1! { Gukesh misses his chance to create his own counterplay } 39... g3+ 40. Ke2 Re3+ 41. Kd1 Nxe4 42. Nxe4) 39... g3+ 40. Ke2 Re3+ 41. Kd1 Rxe1+ $17 42. Kxe1 { With the rooks off the board, the Black knights are ready to wreak havoc on the loose enemy pawns } 42... Ke6 43. Kd1 Ne7! { Black sees his chances, as he heads towards the hole on the e3 square } 44. Ke2 Nf5 45. Ng5+ Ke7 46. Nge4 Ke6 47. Ng5+ Kf6 { Frederik knows, he is close, and says no to the repetition } 48. Nge4+ Ke7 49. Nxc5 bxc5 $19 { Black is now practically a pawn up, as white has a double pawn, with no effective break } 50. Ne4 (50. Nf1 { An attempt to stop Ne3 and defend g2 goes in vain } 50... Nh4 $19) 50... b6 51. Kd3 Nh4 { The pawn is now lost } 52. b4 Nxg2 53. bxc5 bxc5 54. Nxc5 Ne3 55. Ke2 Nxc4 { Black pawns are strongly marching down the board, as white pawns will fall 1 by 1. Amazing display of technique by Frederik in the Knight endgame, as he knocks the World Champion, out of the World Cup in round 3 } 0-1


