{ Annotated by IM Nitish Belurkar https://lichess.org/@/kingnb }
1. e4 c5 2. c3 { Jose Martinez chooses the Alapin, a safe line when he has the lead } 2... Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. d4 e6 5. Nf3 cxd4 6. cxd4 b6 { Abdusattarov goes for a lesser played move, as he finds himself in a must win game } 7. Bd2 Bb7 8. Nc3 Nxc3 9. Bxc3 Na6 10. a3 { Both players already found themselves in unkown waters, but the play being more easier for White } 10... Nc7 11. Bd3 Be7 (11... f5!? { Black forces disruption of the center pawns } 12. exf6 (12. O-O Be7 $15 { With a blunt pair of bishops, White finds it tough to make a good plan } 13. Qe2) 12... gxf6 (12... Qxf6?! 13. d5 Qh6 14. dxe6 Qxe6+ 15. Qe2 $14 { White has 2 very powerful bishops }) 13. O-O Qe7 14. Re1 Qg7 { Complicates matters enough for both sides to have their chances }) 12. Qe2 O-O 13. h4!? { White decides to head towards the Black king! } 13... h6?! { A panic move } (13... f5!? { Black must hit the center } 14. exf6 Rxf6 15. Ne5 d6 16. Nf3 h6 { With open play }) 14. Bd2 { The dark square bishop heads back to where the action is } 14... f5 15. exf6 Bxf6 16. Rh3 { White pieces are now all working in tandem to head to the Black king } (16. Rc1 Ne8 17. O-O Nd6 18. Bb4 $14 { Would be suffient for White to hold an small edge }) 16... d6? (16... Bxf3 { Black should act quick } 17. Qxf3 (17. gxf3 Bxd4 18. Bxh6 Qf6 (18... gxh6 19. Qe4 Bg7 20. Qh7+ Kf7 21. Qg6+ Kg8 22. Qh7+ { Would be enough for Jose Martines to go into the next round }) 19. Bg5 Qe5 20. Qxe5 Bxe5) (17. Rxf3? Bxd4 18. O-O-O Rxf3 19. Qxf3 Qxh4 $17) 17... Bg5 18. Qxf8+! { White sacrifices the queen! } 18... Qxf8 19. hxg5 h5 { The only move for Black to keep balance } (19... hxg5?? 20. Bh7+ Kh8 (20... Kf7 21. Rf3+ Ke8 22. Rxf8+ $18) 21. Bxg5 Nd5 22. Bg6+ Kg8 23. Ke2 $18 { The battery of rooks will be unstoppable }) 20. Rxh5 Nd5 21. Rh4 $14) 17. Rc1 (17. O-O-O Qd7 18. Rg3 Kh8 19. Kb1 $18 { White has tucked away his king and now will target the Black king }) 17... Qd7 18. Bb1 { Jose opts for the more straightforward plan } (18. Ng5! e5 (18... hxg5? 19. hxg5 Bxg2 20. Rh8+!! { Sacrifice the roooook! } 20... Kf7 (20... Kxh8 21. Qh5+ Kg8 22. Bh7+ Kh8 23. Bg6+ Kg8 24. Qh7#) 21. Qh5+ Ke7 22. gxf6+ Rxf6 23. Qg5 $18) (18... Bxg2 19. Rg3 Bd5 20. Qg4 { Threatens Nh7 } 20... Bd8 21. Nh3 Rf6 22. Nf4 $18 { Too many threats for white against the fragile pawns on the king side }) 19. Be4 d5 20. Bh7+ Kh8 21. Qh5 $16 { Whites attack proves too strong for Black }) 18... Nd5? { Allows White to continue with his plan without any resistance } (18... e5! { The time is now to strike for Black } 19. dxe5 dxe5 { Black has managed to create chaos, and find balance }) 19. Qd3 Kf7 { The king on the run to desperately find a safe square } 20. Rg3? (20. g4! Ke7? (20... Ke8 21. g5 hxg5 22. hxg5 Be7 23. Nh4 $18 { White pieces work well in sync, while Black struggles to finds himself misplaced all over the board }) 21. g5 { traps the bishop }) 20... Ke8 { White king is now safe in the center } 21. Kf1 Kd8 22. Re1 Kc7 23. Qe2 Rae8 { Black has bounced back, the king stays safer and the pieces are coordinated too } 24. Bd3 Bc6 25. Kg1 Kb8 26. Bg6 Re7 27. Be4 { Black finds it tough to create an active plan } 27... Bb7 28. Qd3 Rc8 29. Qb3 { White just moves across the board, improving the pieces } 29... Qd8 30. a4 a6 31. Bd3 Ka7 32. Rg4 Qd7 33. Ne5!? { White spots his chance! } 33... Qd8 (33... dxe5 34. dxe5 Bxe5 35. Rxe5 Qd6 36. Re1 { White is preferred due to healthy bishops }) 34. Nc4 g5 35. hxg5 Bxg5 (35... hxg5 { The ideal way to play on } 36. Be4 (36. Rxg5? { Does not work now } 36... Bxd4 $19) 36... Qc7 37. Rc1 Qd7) 36. Rxg5 hxg5 37. Bxg5 { Pawn up and sets up a pin } 37... Qc7 38. Bxe7 Qxe7 39. Be4 Qc7 40. Nd2 { The position remains balanced, but White enjoys an extra pawn } 40... Qg7 41. Nc4 Qc7 42. Nd2 Rh8?! { A desperate attempt from Abdusattarov } 43. Qg3 Qf7 { Eyeing the White king } 44. Nc4 (44. a5 { Would have been better } 44... bxa5 (44... Qh5 45. axb6+ Nxb6 46. f4 $18) 45. Nc4 Qh5 46. f4 { Making an escape route for the king } 46... Qf7 47. Nxd6 Qf6 48. Qf2 $14) 44... Nf4 45. Nxd6 Qf6 (45... Qf8 46. Bxb7 { Begins a sequence of few only moves for both sides to hold on to equality } (46. Nxb7 Qh6 { Would transpose to the game }) 46... Qh6! 47. f3 Nd3 48. Kf1 Qd2 49. Nc8+ Kxb7 50. Qg7+ Kb8 51. Qa7+ Kxc8 52. Qxa6+ Kc7 53. Qa7+ Kc8 54. Qa6+) 46. Nxb7 (46. a5 { White could try on } 46... bxa5 47. Qb3 Bxe4 48. Rxe4 Rh7 49. Nc8+ Ka8 50. Qf3 Nh3+ 51. Kf1 Qxf3 52. gxf3) 46... Qh6 47. f3 Qf6 48. Re3! (48. Rd1?? Ne2+ $19 { Has to be aware of the small tricks }) 48... Rf8?? { The final error by Abdusattarov } (48... Qxd4 49. Qxf4 Qd1+ 50. Kf2 Qd2+ 51. Kg1 (51. Kg3?? Rg8+ 52. Kh4 Qxg2 $19 { The king is in trouble }) 51... Qd1+ { The game ends in a draw }) 49. Nd6 Qxd4 50. Kf1! { Spots it! } 50... Kb8 (50... Qxe3 51. Qg7+ Kb8 52. Qb7#) (50... Qxd6 51. Qg7+ Kb8 52. Qb7#) 51. Nf5 Qe5 (51... Rxf5 52. Rd3 { Using the pin } 52... Qxb2 53. Bxf5 $18) 52. Qg7 { Jose Martinez won a rollercoaster of a game, and won the Round against Abdusattarov with a comprehensive, 2-0 victory! } 1-0


