1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 { Sam Shankland makes a bold choice, the philidor defence with the black pieces } 4. Nf3 (4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 { The early queen trade is known to equalize quick }) 4... Nbd7 5. Bc4 { Vidit opts for the most natural move } (5. g4!? { An interesting pawn sac that has gained traction in recent times } 5... Nxg4 6. Rg1 Ngf6 7. Bc4 { Leads to an equal but complex position for both sides }) 5... Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6 8. a4 Re8 9. h3 (9. Ng5 Rf8 10. Nf3 Re8 { Would just repeat }) 9... h6 10. a5 exd4 { Sam decides to break open the center } (10... Bf8 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Rxe5 13. Bf4 Re8 { Would have been another way to play }) 11. Nxd4 Bf8 12. Bf4 Nc5 { Black targets the white center } 13. e5 (13. Qf3 Ne6 14. Bxe6 Bxe6 15. a6 bxa6 16. Rxa6 Bc8 17. Rxc6 Bb7 18. Rc4 d5 $13 { Leads to a very unclear position }) 13... dxe5 14. Bxe5 Ncd7 15. Bf4 Rxe1+ 16. Qxe1 { White enjoys active pieces and healthy space } 16... Nc5 (16... Nb6!? { Forcing trades } 17. axb6 (17. Nxc6 bxc6 18. axb6 Qxb6 19. b3) 17... Qxd4 18. Rxa7 Rxa7 19. bxa7 Qxa7) 17. Qe3 Bd7 18. Be5 Qe7 19. Re1 Re8 { All pieces are battle ready at the center of the board } 20. Qf3 Qd8? (20... Na4! { Black looks to trade more pieces to compensate for the lesser space } 21. Nxa4 Qb4 22. Qc3 (22. Bxf7+ Kxf7 23. Qb3+ Qxb3 24. Nxb3 Bf5 25. Nd4 Bh7 26. Re2 Nd5 { The active pieces compensate the shortage of 1 pawn }) 22... Qxa4 23. b3 Qb4 24. Qa1 Qa3) 21. Re3 $14 { White now seizes the opportunity } (21. Re2 $16 { More ideal } 21... Qxa5 { fails now as } 22. Bxf6 Rxe2 23. Bxf7+ Kxf7 24. Bd8+ { The rook on e3 would have an attack on the White queen } 24... Kg8 25. Bxa5 $18) 21... a6 (21... Qxa5 22. Bxf6 Rxe3 23. fxe3 gxf6 24. Qxf6 $14 { White is strategically better }) 22. b4 Ne6 23. Bxe6? { Misses the opportunity } (23. Bxf6 Qxf6 24. Qxf6 gxf6 25. Ne4! Rd8 (25... Be7 26. Nf5 Kf8 27. c3 $18 { Better pawns and better pieces }) (25... Bg7 26. Nd6 Rb8 27. N4f5 $18 { The knights dominate the ugly bishop pair }) (25... Nxd4?? 26. Nxf6+ Kg7 27. Nxe8+ $18) 26. Nxf6+ Kg7 27. Nh5+ Kg8 28. Nf5 $18 { An extra pawn and attack }) 23... Bxe6 24. Bxf6 Qxf6 25. Qxf6 gxf6 26. Ne4 $14 { White has more chances, but the lesser the pieces, the happier Black is } 26... Be7 27. c3 Kf8 28. g4 { Dampening the bishops } (28. Nc5 Bc8 29. Kf1 { Would have been possible too }) 28... Bc8 29. Nb3 f5 { Black takes his opportunity to open up and get his bishops active } 30. gxf5 Bxf5 31. Nec5 Bc8 { Back to defend the b7 pawn } 32. Kg2 Rd8 33. Kg3 Rd6 34. Ne4 Rg6+ 35. Kh2 Be6 36. Nbc5 f5 { Forcing matters } 37. Nxe6+?! (37. Ng3 Bc8 38. Nd3) 37... Rxe6 { Black senses freedom, finally not forced to defend the b7 pawn with the bishop } 38. Ng3?? { A big error, Vidit misjudges the endgame } (38. Nc5 { The only way to survive } 38... Rxe3 39. fxe3 Bxc5 40. bxc5 Ke7 41. Kg3 Kf7 42. Kf4 Ke6 43. e4) 38... Rxe3 $19 39. fxe3 Bf6 { Black hits the pawns settled on the dark squares } 40. Ne2 (40. Nxf5 Bxc3 41. Nxh6 Bxb4 $18 { Drops another pawn and has 3 connected passers }) (40. c4 Bc3 41. b5 cxb5 42. cxb5 axb5 43. Nxf5 b4 $19) 40... Ke7? (40... Bg5! { Hitiing all the weak White pawn } 41. Nd4 (41. Nf4 Bxf4+ 42. exf4 { The trade benefits the Black king which reaches the pawns quicker } 42... Ke7 43. Kg3 Kd6 44. Kh4 Kd5 45. Kh5 Ke4 $18) 41... Bxe3 42. Nxf5 Bd2 $19) 41. Kg3 Ke6 42. c4 { White blocks the entry of the Black king } 42... Be7 { Hitting the weaker target } 43. Nf4+ (43. b5 { Does not work well as } 43... axb5 44. cxb5 cxb5 45. Nd4+ Ke5 46. Nxb5 Bd8 $19 { The a5 pawn falls inevitably }) 43... Kd7 44. Nd3 Ke6 45. Kf3 { White has managed to survive a big scare } 45... Bd6 46. e4 fxe4+ 47. Kxe4 Kf6 48. c5 (48. Nc5 { Would have been easier as it would have forced trade of the minor pieces } 48... Bxc5 49. bxc5 Ke6 (49... Kg5?? { Black cannot get greedy } 50. Ke5 Kh4 51. Kd6 Kxh3 52. Kc7 h5 53. Kxb7 h4 54. Kxc6 Kg3 55. Kb6 h3 56. c6 h2 57. c7 h1=Q 58. c8=Q $18) 50. h4 h5 51. Kf4 Kf6 52. Ke4 Ke6) 48... Bc7 49. Nb2 Be5 50. Nc4 Bc3 51. Nd6 Bxb4 52. Nxb7 { White defends the 2 pawns, but the knight can be kicked by the Black king } 52... Ke7 53. Kd4? (53. Nd6! { White survives } 53... Bxc5 (53... Bxa5 54. Nf5+ Ke6 55. Nxh6) (53... h5 54. Nf5+ Kf6 55. Nd4 Bxc5 56. Nxc6) 54. Nf5+ Kf6 55. Nxh6) 53... Kd7 (53... h5 { Essential for Black to push the pawn to stop quick attacks by the knight } 54. Kc4 Be1 55. Nd6 Bxa5 $18) 54. Kc4 (54. Nd6 Bxa5 55. Nf7 h5 56. Ne5+ Kc7 57. Nd3 Bd2 58. Kc4 { Would hold on for White }) 54... Be1 $18 { White pawns now are destined to drop soon } 55. Kd3 Bg3 { Traps the knight on b7 } 56. Ke4 Kc7 57. Nd6 Bxd6 58. cxd6+ Kxd6 59. h4 c5 60. h5 Kc6 { Sam Shankland wins the game and advances through, as he shows great temperament and skill, in the endgame, to knock out Vidit } 0-1


