1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 Nf6 6. e3 O-O 7. h3 { A relatively rare choice by Alexander Donchenko, looking to make space for the bishop on h2 early on } 7... c5 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. Bb5 cxd4 10. Nxd4 { Black has the IQP } { [%csl Bd5] } 10... Qb6 11. O-O Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Qxd4 13. exd4 { both the players play with symmetrical pawn structures, heading to an endgame } 13... Be6 14. Bd3 a6 { A commital move } (14... Rfc8 15. Rfc1 h6 16. Rc2 Kf8 { Goes on }) 15. Na4 { White reacts instantly to Blacks last move } 15... Nd7 16. b4! { A great practical decision, opening space on the queen side, and gaining great control of the c5 square } 16... Bf6 (16... Bxb4 17. Rfb1 a5 18. a3 Be7 19. Rxb7 $14 { With the more active pieces, White is preferred }) 17. Be3 Nb8!? { Black tries to manouver the knight to c6, and hit at the d4 pawn } (17... Rfc8 18. Rfb1 h5 19. Nc5 Nb8 20. Nxb7 Nc6 { Would be equally interesting }) 18. Nb6 Ra7 { The rook is trapped on a7, but White cannot get there } 19. f4 Bd8 (19... Nd7 { Pushing back the knight } 20. Na4 b5 21. Nc5 Nb6 { More active play } 22. a4 bxa4 23. Nxa4 Nxa4 24. Rxa4 Rc7 25. Rxa6 Rc3) 20. Na4 (20. f5!? { White could get a bishop pair for himself } 20... Bxb6 21. fxe6 g6 (21... fxe6?? 22. Bxh7+ Kxh7 23. Rxf8 $18) 22. exf7+ Rxf7 23. Rxf7 Kxf7 24. Be2 Nc6 25. Rd1 Nxb4 26. Bf3) 20... Nc6 21. a3 f5?! { Black tries to lock the center, the knight has journeyed to c6, and wishes, it could be at e4 } 22. Rac1 Bf6 23. Rfe1 Raa8 (23... Bxd4? { Is not a free pawn } 24. Rxc6 bxc6 (24... Bxe3+ 25. Rxe3 bxc6 26. Rxe6 $18) 25. Bxd4 $18) (23... Nxd4 24. Nb6 Nc6 25. Bc5 Bd4+ 26. Bxd4 Nxd4 27. Kf2 $18 { White is happier and the Black pieces struggle }) 24. Nc5 Bc8 { Black is forced to return his bishop to the starting position } 25. Bb1 Nxd4? { Black grabs the pawn, but White is happier without it } (25... Rd8 26. Bf2 Rb8 27. Kh2 Kf8 28. Red1 $14 { White enjoys marginal edge, but the game goes on }) 26. Ba2 $16 { Hitting at the weak diagonal, that has been abandoned by the light square Black bishop } 26... Rd8 27. Bf2 (27. Rcd1? { Should not rush } 27... Nc2 28. Rxd5 Rxd5 29. Bxd5+ Kh8 30. Re2 Nxe3 31. Nb3 (31. Rxe3 Bd4 $19) 31... Rb8 (31... Nxd5 32. Re8#) 32. Rxe3 Bd7) 27... Kf8 28. Na4! $18 { A great retreat. The knight heads back again to b6, but this time with more motives } 28... b5 29. Nb6 Rb8 30. Nxd5 { White is now in full control, Black pieces are passive and closer to being arranged again into starting position } 30... Rd6 31. Nxf6 gxf6 32. Kf1 { Taking careful steps } (32. Rcd1 { Walks into tricks } 32... Ne2+ 33. Kf1 Rxd1 34. Rxd1 Nc3 35. Ra1 Nxa2 36. Rxa2 { Black happy with the exchanges }) 32... Bb7 33. Rc7 { The monstrous rook gets in, unchallenged } 33... Be4 34. Rxh7 Rbd8 35. Rd1 Ne6 36. Rh8+ (36. Bc5 { Would have been quick too! } 36... Nxc5 37. Rh8+ Ke7 38. Rxd8 Rxd8 39. Rxd8 Kxd8 40. bxc5 { And as the pieces are chopped off the board the h pawn marches to the end }) 36... Ke7 37. Rxd8 Rxd8 38. Rxd8 Nxd8 39. Bc5+ Kd7 40. h4 { Passed pawns must be pushed } 40... Ne6 41. g3 Bd3+ 42. Ke1 Ng7 43. Bf7 { The Black king finds it impossible to get to the king side } 43... Bc4 44. Bg6 { Alexander wins the game and slays the another player after Anish Giri that has already qualified for the Candidates event, and heads on to the next round! } 1-0


