{ Annotated by IM Nitish Belurkar https://lichess.org/@/kingnb }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 4. e4 { Alexey Sarana, opts for a sharp line } 4... dxe4 5. Nxe4 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 Qxd4 7. Bxb4 Qxe4+ { Jose Martinez is up for the challenge, as he accepts the extra pawn, that comes along with the complications } 8. Be2 Na6 (8... Qxg2? { Is too greedy } 9. Bf3 Qg5 10. Ne2 $16 { White is ready to pounce, while Black only has the queen ready for battle }) 9. Ba5 { Threatens a mate on d8 } 9... f6 10. Nf3 (10. Qd8+ { Is now met with } 10... Kf7 11. Nf3 b6 12. Bc3 Bb7 { Black unravels his pieces } 13. Qd2 (13. Qd7+ Ne7 14. Qxb7 Nc5 15. Qc7 Rhc8 16. Qg3 Nf5 17. Qg5 h6 18. Qh5+ g6 19. Nd2 gxh5 20. Nxe4 Nxe4 { A very long line that gives equal chances to both }) 13... Ne7) 10... b6 11. Nd2 Qf4 (11... Qxg2?? 12. Bf3 Qg5 13. Bxc6+ $18) 12. Bh5+ g6 13. Bf3 { White has forced Black to commit to pushing the pawns, and target them as weaknesses } 13... Qe5+ 14. Kf1 Qc7 15. Bc3 e5 { Black is now awaiting his chances to develop the pieces } 16. Ne4 Bf5 17. Nd6+ (17. Qa4 { More ideal play } 17... Nb8 18. h4 Nd7 { In order to get the g8 knight out, Black must defend f6 } 19. h5 O-O-O 20. hxg6 Bxg6 21. Re1 $13) 17... Kf8 18. Nxf5 gxf5 19. Qa4 Nc5 20. Qxc6 { Getting back the pawn, but the position is far from easy yet } 20... Qxc6 21. Bxc6 Rd8 22. Bf3?! { Not the bet square to rest the bishop } (22. g3 Ne7 23. Bg2 { The better square for the bishop }) 22... Ne7 { Black heads out with his pieces and he gets a strong center of pawns } 23. b3 Kg7 24. Re1?! (24. Rd1 { White should look to trade pieces } 24... Ne4 25. Be1) 24... Ng6 25. g3 Rd3 $17 { The ugly placement of the bishops comes under attack } 26. Re3 Rhd8 { Black is now ready to charge } 27. Be2 (27. Ke2 e4 28. Bh5 f4 { Finaly, the pawns roll down the board to take control } 29. Rxd3 Rxd3 30. Rc1 f3+ 31. Kf1 a5 $19) 27... R3d7 { Preserving the rooks is essential } (27... Rxe3?! 28. fxe3 a5 29. Kg2 $15 { Gives White a chance to breathe }) 28. Rg1 { The rook struggles to get out } (28. Kg2? f4 29. gxf4 exf4 30. Rh3 Ne4 $19 { Black owns the board, White just spectates }) 28... Ne4 (28... f4 { Was the right time to move in } 29. gxf4 exf4 30. Rh3 Ne4 31. Be1 Nd2+ 32. Kg2 Re7 $17) 29. Be1 Nd2+ 30. Kg2 (30. Bxd2? Rxd2 31. a3 Ra2 32. b4 Rdd2 $19 { The rooks make their way in and freeze White }) 30... f4 { It is now time to get in } 31. Rc3 (31. gxf4 { Important to make this trade } 31... exf4 32. Rc3 Re7 33. Bg4 Ne4 34. Rc1 $15 { White tries to cling on }) 31... e4 { Black senses it, the e pawn is now active } 32. Bg4 (32. gxf4 Nxf4+ 33. Kh1+ Kf7 34. Bg4 Rd3 { Whites fate will be decided soon } 35. Rxd3 Nxd3 36. Bxd2 Nxf2+ 37. Kg2 Nxg4 $19) 32... Rd3 33. Rc2 (33. Rxd3 Rxd3 34. gxf4 Nxf4+ 35. Kh1 Kh6 36. Bxd2 Rxd2 37. Bf5 Nd3 $19) 33... Ne5 $19 { The final piece into the attack } 34. Bf5 Ndf3 { The knight jump all over creating havoc } 35. Bxe4 (35. Rf1 { Is futile as } 35... Nd4 $19 { fork }) 35... Nxg1 36. Bxd3 Ngf3 (36... Nxd3?? { Must be careful } 37. Bc3 { The knight is trapped on g1 } 37... Kg6 38. Kxg1) 37. Bc3 Rxd3 38. b4 Nd4 39. Bxd4 f3+ { Jose Martinez' knights jumped across the board and pressed the white pieces to perfection, as Black won a comfotable game } 0-1


