{ Annotated by IM Nitish Belurkar https://lichess.org/@/kingnb }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { The Italian was the choice made by Pragg for the tie-break game with the White pieces } 3... Nf6 4. d4 { An agressive setup } (4. d3 { Generally been the choice used by White to get a more non forcing game }) 4... d6 { Daniil Dubov decides to avoid the complexities } (4... exd4 { Leads to various complex lines } 5. O-O { The more common gambit } (5. e5 Ne4 6. Qe2 Nc5 7. O-O Ne6 8. c3 d5 9. exd6 Bxd6 10. Bg5 Be7 $13 { Interesting line, goes on }) 5... Nxe4 6. Re1 d5 7. Bxd5 Qxd5 8. Nc3 Qd7 9. Nxe4 Be7 10. Bg5 O-O 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Nxd4 Bd7 { White does regain the pawn, but Black gets a comfortable position }) 5. d5 (5. dxe5 { Does not promise much for White } 5... dxe5 6. Qxd8+ Nxd8 7. Nxe5 Bd6 8. Nd3 Nxe4) 5... Nb8 { Daniil wants the knight to get to d7 } (5... Ne7 { The more common idea } 6. Nc3 g6 { Brings on a different setup }) 6. Nc3 Be7 7. a4 a5?! { This prophylactic decision weakens Blacks hold on the position } 8. Qe2 (8. h3!? { Preventing Bg4, and hinting at a probable king side attack } 8... Na6 9. Be3 O-O 10. g4 Nb4 11. Qe2 c6 12. O-O-O $16 { White enjoys the abundant space and attacking prospects }) 8... c6 9. h3 { Pragg spots it now } 9... Na6 10. O-O (10. Be3 O-O 11. O-O-O $16 { Hinting at a kingside attack for White }) 10... O-O 11. Rd1 Qc7 12. Bg5 (12. Be3 { The better square for the bishop } 12... Nb4 13. Bb3 Bd7 14. Nd2 $16) 12... h6 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Nd2?! { Pragg misjudges the plan for the position } (14. Bxa6 { It is essential to trade the knight for the bishop } 14... Rxa6 15. Nd2 Ra8 16. Ra3 Be7 17. Nc4 $14) 14... Nc5 { Daniil swings the knight at the center } 15. Ba2 (15. Nb3 Nd7 { Denying the trade now }) 15... Be7 { Black hints at a new plan } 16. Nc4 Bd7 17. Rab1 { White wants b4 } 17... Rad8 (17... Be8 { A very deep move that stops white from pushing b4 } 18. b4 axb4 19. Rxb4 b5 { The reason why Be8 is essential! } 20. Ne3 (20. axb5 cxb5 21. Ne3 (21. Nxb5 Bxb5 22. Rxb5 Rxa2 $19) 21... Ra3 22. Qe1 Bg5 $19 { The Black pieces active and press White completely }) (20. dxc6 { Does not attack the bishop anymore, and does not give White the extra tempo }) 20... Nxa4 $17) 18. b4 (18. Nxa5! { More trades } 18... Nxa4 (18... Qxa5 19. b4 Qa7 20. bxc5 Qxc5) 19. Nxc6 Bxc6 20. dxc6 Nxc3 21. bxc3 bxc6) 18... axb4 19. Rxb4 Ra8 { The rook gets back to the half open file } 20. Nb6 Ra7 21. Nxd7?! { A rushed decision } (21. Bc4 { White should hold the knight on b6 } 21... Be8 22. Ra1 Nd7 23. Rab1 Nc5 24. Ra1) 21... Qxd7 22. Qf3 (22. Qg4 Qxg4 23. hxg4 Rfa8 24. Bb3 Kf8 { Leads to a solid endgame }) 22... Raa8 23. Qf5 Qc7 { Black avoids the trade, as the White queen roams the king side alone } 24. Qg4 Kh7 25. h4 Bd8!? { Black decides to find a good spot for the bishop, heading towards the queen side } 26. h5 Qe7 27. dxc6?! bxc6 { The trade favours Black } 28. Bb3 (28. Ne2 { Getting away from the immediate Ba5 threats } 28... Nxa4 29. Bc4 Nc5 30. Ng3 g6 $17 { Position is still complex }) 28... Ba5 $17 { The bishop finds its purpose } 29. Rc4 Rad8 30. Qf3 Kh8 (30... f5! { Breaking open the center } 31. exf5 (31. Rxc5 dxc5 32. Rxd8 Qxd8 $19) 31... d5 { Pawnstorm! } 32. Rxc5 (32. Rg4 e4 33. Qe3 Nxb3 34. cxb3 Rxf5 $19 { Black position is far superior }) 32... Qxc5 $19) 31. Ne2 d5 { Daniil Dubov finally strikes } 32. exd5 cxd5 33. Rg4 (33. Rxd5 e4 34. Qf5 Rxd5 35. Qxd5 Rd8 { White queen is stuck, as the rook heads to d1 } 36. Qxc5 (36. Qf5 Rd1+ 37. Kh2 Qh4+ 38. Qh3 Qxf2 $19 { Too many threats! }) (36. Rxc5 Rxd5 37. Rxd5 Qb4 $19 { White does not have enough for the strong Black queen }) 36... Rd1+ 37. Kh2 Qh4#) 33... e4 34. Qf5 e3 (34... Bc7 { A strong alternative } 35. Bxd5 (35. Rxd5 Nxb3 36. Rxe4 (36. cxb3 Rxd5 37. Qxd5 Rd8 38. Qc4 Rd1#) 36... Qc5! { queen sacrifice! } 37. Rxc5 (37. Rxd8 Rxd8 38. Qxc5 Nxc5 $19) 37... Rd1#) (35. g3 e3 36. f3 Nxb3 37. cxb3 Be5 $19) 35... Qe6!! { A beautiful queen sacrifice! } 36. Bxe6 (36. Qxe6 fxe6 37. Nc3 exd5 $19) 36... Rxd1#) 35. Bxd5? (35. f3 { Would have been better resistance } 35... Bc7 36. Rgd4 Qe6 37. Qxe6 fxe6 38. Rb4 Rb8 $17) 35... exf2+ 36. Qxf2 (36. Kxf2 Rfe8 37. Qf3 Nd7 $19 { White struggles to hold together }) 36... Bb6 37. Kh1 (37. Kh2 Nd7 38. Qf3 Ne5 $19) 37... Nd3! { Black now gets material } 38. Qxb6 Qxe2 39. Rxd3 Qxg4 $19 40. Kg1 Qxa4 41. c4 Qa1+ 42. Kf2 Qe5 43. Qd4 Qxh5 { Picking up all the loose pawns along the way } 44. Rg3 Qf5+ 45. Kg1 f6 46. Kh2 Rfe8 47. Qb6 Qh5+ 48. Rh3 Qe5+ 49. Rg3 Qd6 50. Qa7 Re7 51. Qf2 Re5 52. Kg1 Rde8 53. Kf1 { A clean finish from Dubov to eliminate the Indian star, Praggnanandhaa, who has his last chance to book his Candidates spot, through the Grand Chess Tour } 0-1


