{ Annotated by IM Nitish Belurkar https://lichess.org/@/kingnb }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 { Arjun with the Black pieces goes for the mainstream Guico Piano, against the most experienced of World Cup players, Levon Aronian } 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 (5. d4 { Played a lot in the earlier days, has now lost its trend } 5... exd4 6. e5 (6. cxd4 Bb4+ 7. Nbd2) 6... d5 7. Bb5 Ne4 8. cxd4 Bb4+ { Is still in vast opening territory }) 5... a5 { Stopping potenial b4 from White } 6. O-O d6 7. Re1 O-O 8. Nbd2 Be6 9. Bb5 { White avoids the trade of the light squared bishop, and tuck itself later into c2 } 9... Ba7 { Black wants to relocate the c6 knight, and avoids any immediate d4 attacks on the bishop } (9... Qb8 { A common idea used in these positions } 10. Nf1 Qa7 11. Be3 Bxe3 12. Nxe3 Ne7) 10. Nf1 Ne7 { Going with the plan } 11. d4 Ng6 12. Ng3 c6 13. Bf1 { White heads his bishop back home } 13... Bg4 14. Be3 exd4 { Arjun commits in the center } 15. cxd4 d5 16. e5 Ne8 17. Be2 (17. h3 { Would be more forcing } 17... Bxf3 18. Qxf3 f6 19. Qh5 fxe5 20. dxe5 Bxe3 21. Rxe3) 17... f6 { Breaks open the center } 18. exf6 Nxf6 19. Qb3 Bxf3 { Arjun decides his pair of knights are more essential } 20. Bxf3 Qd7 21. Rad1 h6 22. Be2 Rae8 { Black is setup for action } 23. Bd3 Nh4 24. f3 Nh7!? { Rerouting the knights towards the White king } 25. Bb1 Ng5 26. Qc2 (26. f4 Nh3+ 27. gxh3 Qxh3 28. Qc2 Nf3+ { Gives Black nothing substantial } (28... Rf6!? 29. Qf2 Rfe6 $13 { Unclear }) 29. Kh1 Nxe1 30. Qh7+ Kf7 31. Bg6+ Kf6 32. Rxe1 $18) 26... g6 { Arjun goes for the subtle move } (26... Ngxf3+! { A vicious blow! } 27. gxf3 Rxf3 28. Qh7+ (28. Bf2 Rxe1+ 29. Rxe1 (29. Bxe1 Qg4 30. Kh1 Nf5 $19 { Blacks vicious attack compensates the lack of a piece }) 29... Qh3 30. Be3 Rxe3 31. Rxe3 Bxd4 $19) 28... Kf7 { The knight holds the g6 square } 29. Bf5! { White needs to desperately stop Qh3 } (29. Rf1 Rxe3 $19) 29... Nxf5 30. Rf1 Rexe3 31. Nxf5 Qxf5 32. Qxf5+ Rxf5 33. Rxf5+ Ke6 34. Rf8 Kd6 35. Rf7 Re4 36. Rxb7 Bxd4+ 37. Kf1 g5 $17 { And after a vey lengthy line, Black has the upper hand }) 27. Kh1 Qf7 (27... Bb8 { Getting in the final piece would be interesting } 28. Bf2 Nh3!? { Leads to a crazy position } 29. gxh3 Qxh3 30. Rg1 (30. Bg1 Bxg3 $19 { The inclusion of the bishop works out }) 30... Re6 31. f4 Rxf4 32. Rd3 Nf3 33. Rg2 Nh4) 28. Qf2 Bb8 29. Nf1 Nf5 { Forced to retreat } 30. Bd2 Bc7 31. Ne3 (31. Bxf5 { An important trade to get off the knight } 31... gxf5 32. b4 a4 33. b5 cxb5 34. Bb4 Rxe1 35. Rxe1 Re8 36. Rxe8+ Qxe8 37. Qc2 Qd7 38. Ne3) 31... Nxe3 32. Bxe3 Kg7 33. Qf1 Re6 (33... Bxh2! { A cheeky pawn grab! } 34. Kxh2 (34. Bxg5 Bg3 35. Rxe8 Rxe8 36. Bd2 Qf6 $19 { Forces checkmate via Qh4 }) 34... Rxe3 35. Rxe3 Qf4+ 36. Kh1 Qxe3 $19) 34. Bg1 Rfe8 35. Rxe6 Rxe6 36. a3 { White is not in a position to make waiting moves on the queen side } (36. Qd3 Qf4 37. Rf1 { threatening g3 } 37... Qh4 38. Qc3 h5 39. Bd3 $13) 36... h5 $17 37. Qf2 Qf4 { The queen heads in } 38. Re1?? { The big blunder } 38... Nh3!! { A brilliant move to end the game! Arjun gets the better of the 2 time World cup winner, Levon Aronian. } 0-1


